devlog #001 — on building things you actually want to build

03/02/2026
I switched Piltover to Zaun — it fits better. The dark, industrial underbelly of a technological giant maps well to the role I had in mind.
But beyond the worldbuilding, something more interesting came up while designing this.

I've been struggling to write code outside of work lately. After a full day of sitting next to people in back-to-back meetings, listening to agents, agents, agents on repeat — I feel a deep, almost physical aversion to opening my laptop when I get home. I know it matters for my career. I know agents are the thing right now, and that staying sharp on this stuff translates directly to employability, salary, and stability. And yet — the more I feel like I should be doing it, the less I want to.
Then this happened. A conversation that started with a fake news headline about AI being used in warfare turned into designing a multi-agent geopolitical simulation from scratch — Game Theory, LangGraph, Neo4j, LoL lore. And for the first time in weeks, maybe months, I genuinely didn't want to stop.

I think the distinction worth naming here is: this isn't burnout from coding. It's burnout from performative coding.
There's a real difference between building something because a question genuinely interests you, and building something because you're afraid of falling behind. The market has turned programming into a kind of collective anxiety — everyone chasing the same topic of the week. Agents today, something else tomorrow. It's exhausting not because it's hard, but because it often feels hollow.
What made today different was that nothing was at stake. No one asked for it. It won't go on a performance review. There was no deadline. It was just an idea that grew naturally out of curiosity — how would a real multi-agent system model geopolitical decision-making? — and that question turned out to be genuinely interesting to me.
There's a Nietzsche framing I keep coming back to: the difference between doing something as an expression of what you want to become, versus doing something out of fear. Everything built from fear drains you. Everything built from genuine will tends to energize.

My takeaway: don't force the balance. When the urge to build shows up on its own, follow it without guilt. When it doesn't, don't perform it.
The simulation will still be here when it comes back.
